## 1. Executive Summary

Mr. Brazelton has produced a thoughtful, internally consistent three-variant cargo pod concept for an electromagnetic mass-driver-fed lunar resupply chain. The structural argument — that uncrewed cargo unlocks a higher-G launch envelope than crewed vehicles — is correct and useful. The three-variant taxonomy (hardened bulk / isolated / liquid-suspended biological) is a legitimate framing.

However, the document as submitted does not meet the standard a research paper requires. **My specific findings:**

1. **Trajectory and orbital mechanics are not closed.** The "apogee altitudes" and "Tug catch velocities" presented are vacuum-vertical-launch approximations. The actual problem — a 35° N latitude inclined-rail launch into a ballistic ellipse intercepting an orbiting platform — was not solved. A real trajectory simulation would change every velocity number in the paper.

2. **The 35° N launch site cannot reach equatorial LEO.** The Tug is specified as "stationed in equatorial LEO (~400 km, 0° inclination preferred)." A Hazel Green, Alabama launch (latitude 34.93° N) cannot deliver a payload to 0° inclination without a plane-change maneuver costing ~4.4 km/s — far more than the Tug delta-v budget claims. **This invalidates the mission architecture as written.**

3. **The "Tug catches the pod at 3–4 km/s relative velocity" claim is not rendezvous, it is impact.** Operational rendezvous requires terminal closing rates below 0.1 m/s. The paper conflates ballistic intercept (where two objects pass close at hypersonic speed) with capture (where two objects are co-moving and one grapples the other). These are different problems by orders of magnitude.

4. **TPS sizing is unsupported and likely wrong.** PICA-X is qualified for atmospheric *entry* at speeds up to roughly 8 km/s (Stardust returned at 12.4 km/s using PICA, but that is a different ablator profile than PICA-X). The paper applies it to atmospheric *exit*, which has a fundamentally different heating profile (rapidly thinning atmosphere, different stagnation point dynamics, different ablation behavior). Citing 25 mm as "sufficient" without CFD or arc-jet support would not survive a Critical Design Review.

5. **Cost figures are not derived.** $54/kg, $467/kg, $4,190/kg are presented as engineering outputs but appear to be reasoned guesses. No bill of materials, no labor estimate, no production-rate analysis, no comparison-class anchor (e.g., Cygnus per-kg cost, current CLPS per-kg). My CLPS payload work suggests the realistic floor for new lunar-delivery hardware in low production is several orders of magnitude higher than the figures presented.

6. **Several citations in the references section appear to be fabricated.** This is the most serious issue. The author has acknowledged this in a separate communication. Any document carrying a "References" section that the reader cannot verify is not a research paper. It is a story.

7. **The liquid suspension density-attenuation math is wrong.** I will detail this in §6.

I recommend the document be reissued as a "**Design Concept Memorandum**" with all citations purged or replaced with verified references, all numerical claims tagged for sourcing, and all trajectory and architecture claims either solved or explicitly flagged as TBD. This is recoverable. Do not circulate the v0.1 outside Mr. Brazelton's immediate technical circle.

